<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Can you imagine the high horses that would be mounted, the shrill outcry,
were BBC2 to promise a programme in which three men discussed what delighted
and disgusted them about women, femininity and female hygiene? But don't
worry, today's 10 x 10 is politically correct to its enamelled fingertips:
it promises three women discussing what delights and disgusts them about
men, masculinity, and male hygiene. So that's OK (10.20). Three Indian
hucksters are the subject of Under The Sun (9.30 BBC2). Shakeel sells kohl
and sings at Muslim festivals; Ansfar peddles home-made potions, he
admitting 'My balm doesn't work on me, I use Vick'; and Hashmat sells a
magic book and is an alcoholic. The subject of Ross McElwee's documentary
for True Stories (9.35 C4) is his own life and family. He says he is 'more
comfortable filming the family than starting one', though the programme
shows him announcing his engagement. If you have managed to avoid hearing
the score in the first day of the Third Test it will take some strength of
character to switch on (11.50 BBC1) and find out.
</TEXT>
