<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Police threaten 'open conflict': Sheehy urges radical
shake-up of existing structure - Officers warn of consequences
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT was warned by the Police Federation yesterday that it risked
'open conflict' with the police service if it adopted radical proposals for
changing pay and conditions of employment.
Recommendations from a government-appointed inquiry chaired by Sir Patrick
Sheehy, chairman of BAT industries, constitute one of the most radical
packages of change ever proposed in the public sector. It would lead to all
police officers eventually being employed on limited-term contracts, with
pay related to individual performance and the demands of particular jobs.
The Police Federation, which represents all officers up to the rank of chief
inspector, said that the Sheehy recommendations would turn police work from
a vocation into a 'job like any other job'. That would have serious
implications for the way the service operated.
The prospect of conflict was also recognised in a comment by Mr Eric Caines,
a member of the Sheehy inquiry team and former industrial relations director
of the National Health Service. He said the public sector was 'notorious' in
its attitude to change, and many hurdles would have to be overcome before
the recommendations were implemented.
The Police Superintendents' Association warned: 'If the recommendations are
implemented we will not be able to recruit, retain and motivate officers of
the best quality.' But a more positive initial reaction came from Mr John
Burrow, chief constable of Essex and president of the Association of Chief
Police Officers. He welcomed the recommendations for a new pay formula and
more managerial freedom for chief constables.
The report - combined with Monday's Home Office white paper proposing the
restructuring of police authorities on more businesslike lines and other
changes - sets the scene for the biggest programme of police reform in
modern times.
Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, will consider reactions to the report
until September before making final decisions on its 272 recommendations.
Many of the proposed changes would require legislation, and a bill is likely
in the autumn.
Introducing the report yesterday, Sir Patrick said that promotion was now
the only reward for efficiency in the police. He said that the system of pay
awards related to length of service was not conducive to efficiency.
</TEXT>
