<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / One in 10 newly qualified teachers 'unsuited' for job
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE IN 10 newly qualified teachers is 'unsuited to teaching', according to
the Office for Standards in Education.
In its first report on the standards of new teachers since Her Majesty's
Inspectorate became a part of Ofsted earlier this year, the watchdog said
the finding 'raises the crucial question of how these students were selected
for training, allowed to complete their course successfully, and gain
appointments'.
It added: 'Both the training institutions and the schools share the
responsibility.'
The inspectors found that those teachers unsuited to the profession were
predominantly unaware that they were unsuited, and that heads also failed to
realise their prob-lems.
Only 54 per cent of new primary teachers felt adequately prepared to teach
reading. The inspectors further called for more work using information
technology to support teaching.
The Department for Education, which is planning to make changes to teacher
training, said the survey highlighted the need for close scrutiny of initial
teacher train-ing.
Mr John Patten, the education secretary, announced proposals to reform
initial teacher training last month which would include more school-based
training for teachers, and new qualifications.
He also advocated relaxing the requirement that teachers of infants should
be graduates. Teachers for children of all other ages would still need to be
graduates, according to the proposals.
Teachers' associations said the Ofsted findings showed that the present
teacher training system was working well.
They pointed to the finding that 71 per cent of lessons taught by new
secondary teachers and 73 per cent by new primary teachers were judged to be
satisfactory or better.
Mr Jeff Holman, assistant secretary of the National Association of Head
Teachers, pointed out that the proportion of 'satisfactory' new teachers
correlated very closely with the proportion of all teachers judged to be
satisfactory.
He said: 'I think it's a very encouraging report. It shows that teachers who
had just come out of college were well prepared by their higher education
training for teaching.'
The National Union of Teachers attributed the high proportion of unsuitable
candidates joining the profession to the high level of unemployment.
The union said: 'The difficulty in getting a job now would persuade many
people to stay in the profes-sion, even if they are not suitable.'
It also said that poor resourcing, particularly in primary schools, made it
difficult for headteachers to monitor new teachers as adequately as they
wished.
The New Teacher in School, A Survey by HM Inspectors in England and Wales
1992. HMSO Publications Centre, PO Box 276, London SW8 5DT. Pounds 6.50.
</TEXT>
