<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Shake-up urged for civil justice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A RADICAL shake-up in the civil justice system to cut costs, reduce delays
and provide more user-friendly justice was called for yesterday by the Bar
and the Law Society.
Ms Hilary Heilbron QC, who chaired a joint working party of barristers and
solicitors, said civil justice was available only to the very rich or the
very poor.
Even for those who could afford to litigate, costs had escalated, delays had
increased and trials had become more complex and took longer, she said.
The working party calls for a re-organisation of the High Court. The Queen's
Bench Division and Chancery Division should be merged into one Civil
Division presided over by the lord chief justice - the Family Division
remaining a separate entity.
A number of specialist courts or case lists should be created. These would
include the commercial court, a company and insolvency list, a jury list, a
judicial review list, a patent court and a revenue list.
Judges would be allocated to these specialised case lists according to their
expertise.
The report calls for courts to exercise greater control over litigation.
Once proceedings have been started the court should remind parties to
litigate quickly or risk having the action struck out. Judges are urged to
take a more interventionist approach in cases to ensure parties focus on the
relevant issues.
More emphasis should be placed on alternatives to litigation, particularly
mediation.
The report has been sent to the lord chancellor for consideration. Ms
Heilbron said most of the recommendations could be implemented without the
need for primary legislation.
</TEXT>
