<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / TGWU seeks to broaden its appeal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TGWU general union is hoping to broaden its appeal by offering a range
of welfare and counselling services to members, former members, and even
non-members, Mr Bill Morris, the general secretary, said yesterday.
Prior to next week's union conference - which is held every two years - Mr
Morris said that the union needed a 'twin-track' strategy of improving
collective bargaining services for those in unionised workplaces while also
providing services such as legal support and debt counselling.
He speculated that such services might be advertised in local newspapers and
offered free to all-comers to improve the union's standing in the community.
'We want to provide a one-stop shop of services to actual and potential
members at our offices,' he said.
The union, which today loses its 70-year-old title of Britain's biggest
union to the Unison public-sector union conglomerate, has recovered
financially since Mr Morris took over two years ago. Last year the union had
a small surplus after a loss of Pounds 12m in 1991.
It is now planning to improve efficiency by spending about Pounds 1.2m on
updating its information technology systems and 'Pounds 5m to Pounds 6m' on
training staff over the next few years.
The union is still losing members but Mr Morris described de-recognition as
only a 'growing irritant' apart from sectors such as oil where it has become
a large problem.
Mr Morris has made some headway in reducing the faction fighting within the
union although he is still constrained by the power of a hard-left group on
the executive.
In spite of his attempt to emphasise the union's industrial role, Labour
party politics will hang over the conference. The union is expected firmly
to reject Mr John Smith's plans for reforming the links between unions and
the party although Mr Morris has been noticeably more conciliatory towards
the Labour leader than Mr John Edmonds, his opposite number at the GMB
general union.
The union is also expected to approve support for a change in the electoral
system and for entering formal merger talks with the GMB. The full merger is
expected to be complete within two to four years. The TGWU is also expected
to enter negotiations with the Ucatt building workers' union over a merger.
</TEXT>
