<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Board named for business school
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANCHESTER University has persuaded Sir Terence Burns, permanent secretary
to the Treasury, and Mr James Ross, chief executive of Cable &amp; Wireless, to
help re-establish Manchester Business School's reputation after last year's
row over its future.
Both will serve on the school's new board, announced yesterday, with Mr Ross
as chairman. The board's predecessor body - a council of 14 business leaders
and former Whitehall mandarins - resigned 13 months ago after Professor Tom
Cannon, the school's director, left amid recriminations about the structure
of the school. The university dissolved the council.
The new board's first job will be to address a deficit at the previously
profitable school. Financial health partly depends on reputation, which in
Manchester's case ranks with Harvard in the US, Insead in France, and London
and Cranfield in the UK because of the quality of its postgraduate
management education.
Documents leaked to the Financial Times show a deficit of Pounds 326,700 at
the end of March - Pounds 706,700 worse than a then-budgeted surplus of
Pounds 380,000.
Professor Martin Harris, Manchester University's vice-chancellor, said
yesterday not all this could be attributed to the row - there was a general
downturn in demand for places on postgraduate courses because of the
recession.
Professor Tony Cockerell, acting director of the school, said cost-cutting
should have improved finances by the end of this term. The school is hoping
to be near break-even on the academic year.
Prof Cannon left after a long row over proposals to federate the business
school with the School of Management at the University of Manchester
Institute of Science and Technology and the university's department of
accounting. The federation has still not been formed.
Also on the new business school board will be Mr Joe Dwek, chairman of
Bodycote International; Mr Robert Hough, chairman of Manchester Ship Canal;
Ms Kzimiera Kanto, finance director of Central Independent Television; Mr
Andrew Gardner, chairman of Boyden World Corporation; Mr Martin Bell,
finance director of Turner and Newall; Mr Tain Macdonald, chairman of SHL
Systemhouse Europe; and Mr Peter Dell, chairman of Ernst &amp; Young Recruitment
Network Practices.
