<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Fall in housing equity withdrawal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AMOUNT of equity withdrawn from housing last year fell to its lowest
level since 1981, the Housing Finance Review published by the Joseph
Rowntree Foundation, the social research organisation, says.
In 1988 consumer demand was boosted by Pounds 21.6bn by withdrawal of equity
from private homes, with more than half the money raised through mortgages
not spent on housing. Last year the figure fell to Pounds 3.5bn.
The review estimates that 1.3m households were living in homes worth less
than their mortgages at the end of last year. The average level of negative
equity was Pounds 2,800.
JRF Housing Finance Review 1993. Joseph Rowntree Foundation, 40 Water End,
York YO3 6LP. Pounds 15.
