<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Growth seen in industry spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONFIDENCE about growth prospects in manufacturing has edged up in the past
month, a survey published today by the Chartered Institute of Purchasing and
Supply, has found, Peter Marsh writes.
The survey of industry purchasing managers spending more than Pounds 250bn a
year says companies are increasing their buying of goods and services in
anticipation of a steady recovery.
The purchasing managers' index, which shows sentiment in industry about an
upturn, was calculated at 53.7 last month, up from 53.0 in May, signalling
better growth prospects.
The survey indicates continuing upward pressure on prices as domestic and
export demand rises. The institute says, however that the trend to rising
prices of imported goods has eased as pressures from last year's devaluation
weaken.
