FT  01 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: N-plant costings attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Public Accounts Committee yesterday accused the government of
complacency in estimating the cost of scrapping nuclear facilities.
Mr Robert Sheldon, the Labour chairman of the House of Commons watchdog on
public spending, expressed fears that a heavy burden could fall on the
taxpayer if present government estimates of the costs proved to be wrong. He
said: 'I see a lot of assumptions made, not taking into account the very
serious consequences if you get it wrong.'
The committee is examining this month's National Audit Office report on
nuclear decommissioning, which put the total cost of scrapping nuclear power
stations and fuel plants, as well as some military facilities, at Pounds
17.9bn. Uncertainty over future nuclear liabilities disrupted the
electricity privatisation three years ago and nuclear facilities were left
in government hands.
Sir Peter Gregson, permanent secretary at the department of trade and
industry, said that the government currently believed that the costs of
decommissioning the facilities of the generators Nuclear Electric and
Scottish Nuclear would be covered by the companies' provisions. The
government has undertaken to pay for the eventual scrapping of the Atomic
Energy Authority's facilities, and some of those of British Nuclear Fuels.
However Mr Michael Stern, Conservative MP for Bristol North West, said that
the government's record of estimating decommissioning costs had been
'abysmal'.
