<DATE>930701
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Mates's allegations on Polly case
rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS, ANDREW JACK and JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVIDENCE emerged yesterday to contradict many of the allegations in Mr
Michael Mates's resignation speech concerning the conduct of the
investigations into Mr Asil Nadir, the fugitive businessman.
Mr Mates said in his speech: 'The SFO launched a highly publicised raid on
October 30 1990 on the headquarters of PPI . . after the company was in
administration . . beginning a process of trial by media.'
Journalists were present at the time of the raid on the company, as they
were during other SFO raids such as when Mr Kevin Maxwell and Mr Ian Maxwell
were arrested. PPI was in administration at the time.
Since the time of Mr Nadir's arrest in December 1990 - and until he skipped
bail in May with little likelihood of returning - newspapers were in fact
constrained by potential contempt of court in what they said, for fear of
prejudicing his trial. 'The SFO did not go to northern Cyprus as requested
by Mr Nadir's defence lawyers, even though they visited the island to make
other criminal inquiries in the past.'
Foreign Office officials say the northern Cyprus authorities have adopted a
two-track policy for access of British police. There is full co-operation in
waiving the need for official paper on issues such as drugs and the return
of deported northern Cypriots to the island.
Whenever the Nadir case is raised, northern Cyprus insists that cooperation
must be conducted formally government-to-government which the Foreign Office
cannot allow because the UK does not recognise the state diplomatically.
The Metropolitan Police says that two officers mentioned by Mr Mates were on
the island for deportation duties unrelated to Mr Nadir. One senior police
officer yesterday conceded it may have been possible that one or two of the
officers may have asked about Mr Nadir in conversations with local people,
but they were doing so in personal capacity and did not form part of
official investigations.
'There is evidence of improper collusion between a senior officer of the
Inland Revenue and the SFO.'
Mr Michael Allcock, head of the Inland Revenue's special office 2, which
deals with high-profile and international tax investigations, was suspended
in September last year and is under police investigation. Mr Michael Jones,
his solicitor, yesterday stood by his earlier statement that his client was
'instrumental in the detection of Mr Nadir's affairs and the subsequent
referral thereof to the Serious Fraud Office.'
It is understood that Mr Allcock passed to the Stock Exchange some of the
information he came across during an investigation into Mr Nadir's tax
affairs. The Exchange and the Inland Revenue swap information on an informal
basis, according to officials. But the Inland Revenue said it is by law not
permitted to release details of taxpayers' affairs to third parties except
when ordered to by the courts.
Mr Jones does not deny that as part of his job Mr Allcock may have had some
contact with the SFO. He strongly rejects the suggestion that this could
amount to anything improper. He said nothing he had been told by the police
indicates that Mr Allcock's suspension had anything to do with the Nadir
case, although Mr Nadir's camp has accused Mr Allcock of being part of a
conspiracy against him. Mr Jones understands that his client was suspended
pending an investigation into allegations of corruption and bribery. He said
no criminal charges have yet been brought and Mr Allcock has not so far been
interviewed by police.
'Papers from documents taken by the SFO in the October 1990 raid were passed
to the administrators.'
Administrators to PPI at accountants Touche Ross confirmed that they did
receive some papers from the SFO after the raid at the time of
administration, but said they related to the company and they were therefore
entitled to receive them.
Court-ordered raids on Mr Nadir's property coordinated by Mr Neil Cooper,
his trustee in bankruptcy, took place earlier this year. These removed a
number of Mr Nadir's personal effects including his diaries. Mr Cooper says
he only took this action as a final resort because Mr Nadir refused to
cooperate.
'Improper influence has been exercised by the SFO when it claimed police
were investigating an alleged attempt to bribe the trial judge, Mr Justice
Tucker. The police had never declared their intention to do so.'
When the allegations were first made in the court, they were taken seriously
by both the SFO and the Metropolitan police investigating them. They were
later dismissed as an attempt to destabilise the trial.
'The SFO suggested a conspiracy to pervert the course of justice by Mr
Nadir, Mr Anthony Scrivener, his defence counsel, Mr Wyn Jones, Metropolitan
Police assistant commissioner, and Mr Justice Tucker. This was unfounded.'
Since the hearing was in camera, it is unclear whether the allegations were
made by counsel to the SFO or the Department of Public Prosecutions. But the
suggestions were never taken seriously by anyone who was in the hearings.
'Whose agenda was being served by publication (of Mr Mates' letter to the
attorney-general)?'
Mr Mates says only Mr Nadir, the attorney-general and the SFO had copies.
The SFO claims its investigators did not have copies. Others suggest it may
be in Mr Nadir's interest to leak information which makes his chance of
obtaining a fair trial in the UK impossible.
</TEXT>
