<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Steady hands deliver a bucket of
cold water / Sizing up the attorney-general
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER THE excitable scenes surrounding Tuesday's Commons attack on the
Serious Fraud Office by Mr Michael Mates, the former Northern Ireland
minister, it fell yesterday to Sir Nicholas Lyell, the attorney-general, to
throw a bucket of cold water over the smouldering affair. He did not
disappoint.
Sir Nicholas, as attorney-general the government's senior legal adviser and
the man charged with policing the processes of prosecution outside Scotland,
is not one of Westminster's more charismatic characters.
Aged 54, he is the epitome of the cool top-drawer barrister who, it could
easily be forgotten, is also a politician. He has a dual role which has
increasingly prompted some lawyers to question whether it is any longer
appropriate to have someone elected on a party label who is also on hand to
provide key legal advice.
Regarded as a paid-up member of the 'safe pair of hands' club, he restored
an air of considered calm to yesterday's Commons proceedings, praising the
SFO for its record and pledging a system of prosecution conducted without
'fear or favour, affection or ill-will'.
Only once, in response to a jibe from Mr Dennis Skinner, did he raise his
voice, admonishing the Labour MP for Bolsover for asking 'idiotic
questions'.
Before entering parliament for super-safe Hemel Hempstead - now
Mid-Bedfordshire - in 1979, Sir Nicholas specialised in commercial and
industrial law and gained a reputation as a tenacious if somewhat
unglamourous advocate.
He became attorney-general after last year's general election. His previous
jobs were social security minister and solicitor-general.
Sir Nicholas has attracted his fair share of controversy. He came under
attack for his advice to ministers in the Matrix Churchill case that they
had no alternative but to ask the courts to prevent publication of official
documents where publication was against the public interest.
He was also criticised for his advice over the social opt-out clause of the
Maastricht bill and for his handling of the row over whether the Transfer of
Undertakings (Protection of Employment) regulations apply to the
contracting-out of public services.
Sir Nicholas's standing among barristers remains high. Since entering
parliament he has been given credit by the Bar for having appeared in court
far more often than his predecessors.
One QC said: 'His main disadvantage is that he didn't gain much experience
at the Bar in the administrative and regulatory issues that he is now having
to deal with.'
Not everything has gone smoothly for Sir Nicholas away from Westminster. He
is one of a number of senior Conservative politicians who face huge losses
as a result of their membership of Lloyd's. Sir Nicholas became a Name in
1973 and last year was a member of 23 syndicates - including two which have
made big losses.
</TEXT>
