<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Every allegation was 'carefully
examined'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Nicholas Lyell, attorney-general, yesterday agreed to publish
correspondence between him and Mr Michael Mates, former Northern Ireland
secretary, over the Asil Nadir case. But in a Commons statement he rejected
Mr Mates's call for an independent inquiry. He said a trial for Mr Nadir was
still fixed for October 4.
Sir Nicholas told MPs that it was 'perfectly proper' for an MP to make
representations to him 'about any anxieties they may have concerning the
conduct of a prosecution'.
Between September 1991 and May 10, 1993, Mr Mates made representations 'on a
number of occasions both in writing and orally on which occasions the
meetings were carefully noted by an official'. Each allegation and concern
raised by Mr Mates 'I caused to be carefully examined with the appropriate
authority or body and following which I wrote back to him in some detail.'
He told the Commons he was 'intensely conscious' of the need to keep
separate the roles of parliament and the political process, and that of the
judiciary, and it was only because of 'the exceptional circumstances' that
he had asked for the discretion of the speaker to enable him to deal with Mr
Mates's points.
He summarised the issues raised by Mr Mates, saying: 'He has accused the
Serious Fraud Office of improperly seeking to harass and prejudice the
defendant by allegedly tipping off the media as to the times and places of
arrests and other aspects of the investigation; of refusing to give proper
consideration to a report prepared by the accountants Binder Hamlyn for the
defence and failing to make proper inquiries in northern Cyprus; of
improperly opening privileged documents; of the allegedly improper seizure
by the trustee in bankruptcy of Asil Nadir's papers and certain personal
effects; and of improper pressures allegedly brought by the SFO on the
judge.'
Sir Nicholas said claims of improper press briefing had all been 'carefully
investigated' adding: 'None was accompanied by any tangible or verifiable
evidence' from Mr Mates. 'On the initial occasion involving the fall of the
Polly Peck share price the press were not even present until after that fall
and until the raid had been in progress for some considerable time.'
It was 'correct that two bags containing some privileged documents were
opened in error by police officers'. But they were not copied and were
returned after the issue of privilege had been determined by an independent
silk.
'The papers and effects seized by the trustee in bankruptcy were also seized
pursuant to an order of the court.'
Sir Nicholas went on: 'The report of Binder Hamlyn is part of the defence
case. The SFO has had no opportunity to scrutinise the supporting documents.
Assertions that their removal to this country would contravene local Cypriot
law have been refuted by independent Cypriot legal advice.
'The SFO has been unable to obtain permission for its officers to
investigate the case in northern Cyprus since each informal application had
been met by the response that approaches must be through diplomatic channels
which the House will appreciate do not exist in the absence of formal
recognition of Turkish republic of northern Cyprus.'
'The alleged conspiracy to bribe the judge is the subject of a separate
police investigation under the supervision not of the SFO but of the
director of public prosecutions. I do not propose to say more about it since
it has been dealt with in court either in camera or subject to reporting
restrictions.'
Apart from publicity surrounding the arrests, he said, all these matters
related essentially to the court proceedings.
'I am of the clear view that it is mistaken and wholly inimical to our
system of justice to set up a so-called independent inquiry into the
handling of such matters in parallel to a trial,' he said.
On the letters, Sir Nicholas said he had previously resisted publication.
'Inevitably they deal with a number of issues which have or may be raised in
the preparatory hearings or the trial which could therefore run the risk of
confusing the issues or from certain view points reflecting adversely on the
defendant.'
</TEXT>
