<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Spotlight shunned by the SFO
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OFFICIALS AT the Serious Fraud Office were largely silent yesterday
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
content to let the attorney-general step into the spotlight to rebut the
allegations of impropriety made by Mr Michael Mates over the office's
handling of Mr Asil Nadir's case.
The brief denial of the allegations issued by Mr George Staple, the SFO
director, a few hours after Mr Mates's speech, remains its only official
comment on the furore.
The office said: 'All the criticisms have been answered - we don't want to
perpetuate this.'
However, the allegations have forced the office on to the defensive. A few
days prior to Mr Mates's statement, senior police investigators were ordered
by the office to shut out all contacts with the press - whether overt or
covert.
Both the police involved and the office have become nervous at the way the
whole controversy has developed. 'This is a political issue that we just
don't want to get drawn into,' said one investigator.
Senior investigators insist there is no conspiracy other than Mr Nadir's own
efforts to undermine their attempts to bring him to justice.
A view widely held among those at the office and others probing the affairs
of Polly Peck is that the campaigning by Mr Nadir and others such as Mr
Mates is serving to diminish any prospect that the fugitive tycoon could
have a fair trial in Britain, should he ever be brought back before the
courts here.
One senior investigator said yesterday: 'Mr Mates had been misled . . . What
his allegations are succeeding in doing is putting a smokescreen around Mr
Nadir.'
The allegations have come at a sensitive time for the SFO, with the Royal
Commission on Criminal Justice due to report next week.
