FT  01 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Irish reform of extradition halted
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE IRISH government yesterday halted progress towards the reform of
controversial procedures for the extradition of terrorist suspects to the
UK.
Mr Albert Reynolds, prime minister, stressed the move was temporary. He said
the hold-up was due to problems that had been uncovered by officials in the
Irish attorney-general's department during the final drafting of a bill
aimed at closing loop-holes in the extradition legislation.
It was emphasised by government sources that the difficulties were legal
rather than political, and would lead only to a delay in ratifying the
changes, which centre mainly on the classification of terrorist firearms
crimes considered to be extraditable. Mr Reynolds said the reform bill would
now be tabled in the autumn.
