<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Howard seeks to calm EC seat row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL Howard, home secretary, last night sought to head off a revolt by
Tory MPs against the bill authorising the creation of six new
Euro-constituencies and increasing the number of MEPs representing the UK
from 81 to 87.
He replied in emollient tones to a series of interruptions from
Euro-sceptics on the Conservative backbenches who, after embarrasing the
government through delaying the passage of the Maastricht bill, turned their
fire on the European parliament.
Sir Teddy Taylor (C Southend East), one of the most outspoken critics of the
European Community, stressed that if the bill were to be defeated all the
member states would be prevented from increasing their representation in the
European parliament.
Mr Howard acknowledged that the tactics employed by the Euro-sceptics
against the Maastricht bill meant that there would be insufficient time for
the proposed boundaries for the new Euro-constituencies to be subjected to
public inquiries.
He explained that two special European parliamentary constituency committees
would fulfil the role normally played by the parliamentary boundary
commissions, and that he hoped they would include some of the members of the
commissions.
Mr Howard looked to the committees to complete their work on boundaries for
five new Euro-constituencies in England and one in Wales by the end of
November.
With the next elections for the European parliament due to take place in
June 1994 there would not be time to hold public inquiries, but written
representations would be considered before MPs were asked to approve the
boundaries of the six new constituencies, he said.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, challenged the decision not to
allocate a new constituency to Scotland.
He also maintained that it would be possible, in spite of time constraints,
for the proposed boundaries for the new constituencies to be subject to
public inquiries.
</TEXT>
