<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / World Trade News: Nafta delay latest blow to Clinton trade
policy - The entire US effort to bring free trade to the Americas has been
thrown into question
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ORDER by a US federal court judge yesterday to delay the North American
Free Trade Agreement for an environmental impact assessment was the latest
blow to a carefully constructed Clinton trade policy, which now seems in
danger of crumbling.
The US scenario for the economic summit next week in Tokyo had President
Bill Clinton appearing with a budget reduction package in hand, along with
Senate and House approval for a renewed fast-track negotiating authority,
giving the Uruguay Round of global trade negotiations a last lease of life
until December 15.
The president and Mr Kiichi Miyazawa, Japanese prime minister, had also
agreed to produce by next week a negotiating framework to set up the
perimeters of the US-Japanese bilateral trade relationship.
The Japanese political crisis dealt the first setback. Then, last week in
Tokyo, a ministerial meeting - to prepare for a tariff reduction deal by the
US, EC, Canada and Japan - stalled. Talks on a bilateral framework got
nowhere.
Into the increasingly gloomy picture, on Tuesday, came statements by Mr
Edouard Balladur, French prime minister, who provocatively tied a global
trade deal to the US lifting anti-dumping duties on steel. These brought an
outraged reaction from Mr Peter Watson, chairman of the US International
Trade Commission, who demanded an apology.
'The US administrative and quasi-judicial regime affords a significantly
higher degree of due process to foreign respondents than provided by France
through the related EC process,' he said.
The delay of Nafta for an environmental impact statement throws into
question the US administration's entire effort to bring free trade to the
Americas. And according to one prominent Washington trade lawyer, the court
ruling may also apply to a Uruguay Round agreement: 'You can't possibly do
an environmental impact assessment on the whole world economy.'
Even an expedited appeal would take at least two months. The administration
could ignore the judge's order and risk being sued for contempt, but it is
still trying to prove its green credentials.
Mr Clinton's choice of a novice in trade - Mr Mickey Kantor - as his trade
representative has caused concern among US trading partners (particularly
when Mr Kantor trips on EC sensibilities as he did by doing a separate
telecoms deal with Germany).
Still hoping for progress in Tokyo, Mr Kantor yesterday delayed sanctions
against Japan for its closed procurement market in construction. Next week
he will have to prove his mettle, not just against other more experienced
negotiators, but also against the whims of leaders who for six years have
not demonstrated the political courage to agree on trade liberalisation.
</TEXT>
