FT  01 JUL 93 / Western donors to increase aid for Indonesia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDONESIA'S western donors yesterday increased their aid for the coming year
to Dollars 5.1bn, (Pounds 3.4bn) from Dollars 4.9bn, in recognition of its
'excellent' economic performance and development needs.
But several members of the 18-nation consultative group, chaired by the
World Bank since Indonesia's row with the Netherlands over human rights,
raised the issue of 'good governance', which they said was vital to sustain
the country's development. Canada and Belgium were among those said to have
taken this line.
Mr Gautam Kaji, the World Bank's vice-president for East Asia and the
Pacific who chaired the three-day meeting in Paris, acknowledged some donors
brought up the issue of human rights, but said they were pursuing this
bilaterally.
Dr Saleh Afiff, Indonesia's economy minister, had declined to comment on the
concerns in a multilateral forum as, he said, they were being discussed
bilaterally.
