<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Vietnam likely to rejoin IMF
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE CLINTON administration is expected to lift US opposition to Vietnam's
reinstatement in the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund,
allowing the country to clear its arrears and resume borrowing from the
international development institutions.
A plan for France, the UK, Germany and Japan to provide bridging finance to
allow Vietnam to clear its Dollars 140m (Pounds 93.3m) arrears with the IMF
has been ready for some time now, but Vietnam's backers have been reluctant
to move ahead without at least an orange light from the US.
Vietnam experts say the country actually has enough currency reserves to pay
off the arrears on its own, however the bridging finance would avoid
jeopardising Vietnam's economic ratios while opening the door to financing
from the IMF, the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank.
President Clinton is caught between US commercial interests, which have
watched angrily as other countries have entered the promising Vietnamese
market ahead of them, and between the emotionally powerful lobby of families
of US soldiers listed as missing in action during the Vietnam war.
Former President George Bush had outlined a 'road map' towards normal
relations with Vietnam.
This paired progress on the missing in action issue with a step by step
approach to the relaxation of US commercial sanctions.
</TEXT>
