<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Testing times for Franco-German alliance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
INTEREST RATES
Worried about the effect of high German rates on the French economy, Paris
wants the Bundesbank council to cut rates at its meeting today. France has
reduced short-term rates eight times since early April, putting its
short-term rates below those of Germany's. As a result, further French cuts
are becoming more dependent on Bundesbank action.
BOSNIA
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's plea at last week's European Community
summit meeting for the possible lifting of the arms embargo against
Bosnia-Hercegovina's Moslems took France, as well as other EC countries, by
surprise.
ERM
As investors worry about the German economy and France brings down
short-term interest rates below German levels, the French franc has
attracted solid support on the foreign exchanges, threatening the German
mark's anchor function in the ERM.
BANANAS
Germany, whose people eat more bananas per head by far than anywhere else in
the world, is outraged by the European Community regime to restrict cheap
imports. Germany blames above all the French government, which it sees as
seeking to defend the interests of its foreign territories and former
colonies at the expense of free trade.
GATT
France, which views the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade as a vehicle
for US trade hegemonism, finds itself at odds with Germany. On the sensitive
issue of Gatt-proposed farm trade reform, France is adamant that it cannot
accept the deal negotiated by the EC with strong German support.
TELECOMS
Germany says that its 1954 trade treaty with the US prevents it from
implementing EC trade sanctions against US companies. France, supported by
some other EC countries, is incensed and strongly supports the the European
Commission's view that Germany is breaching community law.
</TEXT>
