<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 93 / Hanson in Dollars 3.2bn deal for Quantum Chemical
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HANSON, the Anglo-American conglomerate, yesterday launched an agreed
Dollars 3.2bn (Pounds 2.13bn) bid for Quantum Chemical Corporation of the
US. The price includes Dollars 720m for Quantum's share capital plus the
assumption of Quantum's Dollars 2.5bn of debt.
Quantum, formed in 1987 from National Distillers &amp; Chemical after it sold
its wine and liquor business, and refinanced with heavy borrowings in 1988,
is the leading US manufacturer of polyethylene, a plastic used in packaging,
and products such as toys and automotive components. It is the second
largest retail supplier of propane gas.
The bid marks Hanson's return to the acquisition trail after its failed
Pounds 780m bid for Ranks Hovis McDougall, the UK food company, launched in
October. Hanson was beaten when rival UK conglomerate Tomkins topped its
offer. It also follows Hanson's purchase of a 2.8 per cent stake in Imperial
Chemical Industries in 1991 which, despite fierce speculation, never led to
a bid.
The Quantum bid illustrates the changing style of Hanson's acquisitions.
Lord Hanson, chairman, said: 'Hanson's objective for the 1990s is to build
up its major businesses, while being prepared to make major acquisitions
when the opportunity presents itself. Quantum fits this perfectly.' Mr Derek
Bonham, Hanson's chief executive, said he expected the acquisition would
make 'a positive contribution to Hanson earnings in 1993-94'.
Quantum's profits have slumped in recent years as overcapacity has hit
polyethylene prices. Lord Hanson said the deal had been struck 'near the
bottom of this industry's cycle'.
Mr David Clarke, chief executive officer of Hanson Industries, the
conglomerate's US arm, said a small increase in prices would have a large
impact on profits.
In 1988, the peak of the last cycle, Quantum's operating income was Dollars
759.8m, but in 1992 this fell to Dollars 61.4m. Quantum has also been
burdened with heavy debt. Interest charges have pushed it into losses in
1991 and 1992 and it has a balance sheet deficit of Dollars 471.1m. Hanson
is offering 1.176 of its American Depository Receipts, which each represent
five ordinary shares, for each Quantum share. That values the target's
equity at Dollars 20 a share or at Dollars 720m in all. The share offer
would add 4 per cent to Hanson's share capital.
Quantum is paying interest rates of more than 10 per cent on its debt while
Hanson pays about 5 per cent on its US borrowings. Hanson also plans to
continue cost cutting programmes.
It hopes to complete the deal by September 30, its financial year end. The
company's shares responded with a 4p rise to a London close of 226 1/2 p.
Quantum's shares closed in New York up Dollars 6 1/2 at Dollars 19.
